<div id="review_1194824440" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1194824440" />
    <a title="Emma Iadanza" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/27230324-emma-iadanza"><img alt="Emma Iadanza" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1602279043p2/27230324.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1194824440?book_show_action=true">Feb 08, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Emma Iadanza" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Emma Iadanza" href="/user/show/27230324-emma-iadanza">Emma Iadanza</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/27230324-emma-iadanza?shelf=abandoned">abandoned</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1194824440" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5741314832898117607">Before I started this book, I read some of the other reviews on Goodreads, and I really must say. I agree. I didn&apos;t want to agree at first, but now I do. <br/><br/>Let me say. I did not love this book. I did not despise it. But I simply disliked it it. A lot. I really wanted to like it, but I can&apos;t. <br/><br/>Basically, this woman and her husband/boyfriend(?) buy a house in Tuscany after wanting to and not wanting to and wanting to and not wanting to and really wanting to but having a lot of other things discourage</span>
  <span id="freeText5741314832898117607" style="display:none">Before I started this book, I read some of the other reviews on Goodreads, and I really must say. I agree. I didn't want to agree at first, but now I do. <br /><br />Let me say. I did not love this book. I did not despise it. But I simply disliked it it. A lot. I really wanted to like it, but I can't. <br /><br />Basically, this woman and her husband/boyfriend(?) buy a house in Tuscany after wanting to and not wanting to and wanting to and not wanting to and really wanting to but having a lot of other things discourage them. They fix it up but they really don't do it, a bunch of polish guys do it in the beginning and then she skips over the rest of their restoration. Then she describes nonsensical things that nobody cares about. Then she lists some recipes that nobody will ever cook. Then she makes a lot of references to South American civilizations and goes to visit a bunch of Etruscan tombs. Then she expects you to know everything about her friends. <br />Dante references do not make it better. Nor does her little sense of Italian language. <br /><br />Sometimes the language was nice. The rest of the time, she just kept telling and telling and not showing at all. And she just kept saying "we do this, we do that". If it's a memoir, why is it in the present tense?<br /><br />I do not suggest this book. But I do not completely hate it. Sorry, Frances Mayes!</span>
  <a data-text-id="5741314832898117607" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


